Azure VPN Tunnel Troubleshooting Guide (Route-Based VPN)
This document provides a step-by-step troubleshooting approach for Azure VPN tunnel issues where the connection shows as 'Connected' but no data traffic is flowing.

Step 1: Verify VPN Connection Status
Navigate to Azure Portal → Virtual Network Gateway → Connections.
Check if the status shows 'Connected'. Also verify Data In and Data Out metrics.
Screenshot: VPN Connection Overview Page


Step 2: Check Data Traffic Metrics
Open the VPN connection and review metrics such as Tunnel Ingress and Egress.
If both are 0 bytes, traffic is not flowing.
Screenshot: Metrics Blade


Step 3: Validate VPN Type Configuration
Ensure both Azure and on-prem firewall use Route-Based VPN.
Disable 'Use policy-based traffic selectors' in Azure if enabled.
Screenshot: VPN Configuration Page


Step 4: Remove Custom Traffic Selectors
Navigate to VPN Connection → Configuration.
Remove any custom traffic selectors configured.
Screenshot: Traffic Selector Settings


Step 5: Verify Effective Routes
Go to Azure VM → Networking → Effective Routes.
Ensure remote subnet routes exist with next hop as Virtual Network Gateway.
Screenshot: Effective Routes


Step 6: Check Network Security Groups (NSG)
Ensure NSG rules allow traffic between Azure and on-prem subnets.
Screenshot: NSG Rules


Step 7: Test Connectivity from Azure VM
Use commands like ping and tracert to test connectivity to on-prem resources.
Screenshot: Command Output

Step 8: Validate On-Prem Firewall/NAT Rules
Check NAT rules on Cisco firewall.
Ensure Azure subnet is allowed instead of individual IPs.
Screenshot: Firewall NAT Rules


Step 9: Confirm Bidirectional Traffic
Recheck Azure VPN metrics to confirm both inbound and outbound traffic.
Screenshot: Final Metrics View
